{"title_page": "Oleg Blokhin", "text_new": "{{Eastern Slavic name|Volodymyrovych|Blokhin}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n|name = Oleg Blokhin\n|image = Oleg Blokhin2013.jpg\n|image_size = 250px\n|caption = Blokhin as manager of [[FC Dynamo Kyiv|Dynamo Kyiv]] in 2014\n|full_name = Oleg Vladimirovich Blokhin, Oleh Volodymyrovych Blokhin\n|birth_date = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1952|11|5}}\n|birth_place = [[Kiev]], [[Ukrainian Soviet Socialist Republic|Ukrainian SSR]], Soviet Union\n|height = 1.80 m\n|position = [[Forward (association football)|Forward]]\n|youthyears1 = 1962\u20131969\n|youthclubs1 = [[FC Dynamo Kyiv|Dynamo Kyiv]]\n|years1 = 1969\u20131988\n|years2 = 1988\u20131989\n|years3 = 1989\u20131990\n|clubs1 = [[FC Dynamo Kyiv|Dynamo Kyiv]]\n|clubs2 = [[Vorw\u00e4rts Steyr]]\n|clubs3 = [[Aris Limassol]]\n|caps1 = 432 |goals1= 211\n|caps2 = 41 |goals2= 9\n|caps3 = 22 |goals3= 5\n|totalcaps= 495 |totalgoals= 225\n|nationalyears1=1972\u20131988\n|nationalteam1=[[Soviet Union national football team|Soviet Union]]\n|nationalcaps1= 112 |nationalgoals1= 42\n|medaltemplates=\n{{MedalSport | Men's [[association football|football]] }}\n{{MedalCountry | {{flag|USSR}} }}\n{{MedalCompetition | [[Football at the Summer Olympics|Olympic Games]] }}\n{{MedalBronze| [[1972 Summer Olympics|1972 Munich]] | [[Football at the 1972 Summer Olympics|Team competition]] }}\n{{MedalBronze| [[1976 Summer Olympics|1976 Montreal]] | [[Football at the 1976 Summer Olympics|Team competition]] }}\n|manageryears1=1990\u20131993\n|manageryears2=1993\u20131994\n|manageryears3=1994\u20131997\n|manageryears4=1998\n|manageryears5=1998\u20131999\n|manageryears6=1999\u20132002\n|manageryears7=2003\u20132007\n|manageryears8=2007\u20132008\n|manageryears9=2011\u20132012\n|manageryears10=2012\u20132014\n|managerclubs1=[[Olympiacos F.C.|Olympiacos]]\n|managerclubs2=[[PAOK F.C.|PAOK]]\n|managerclubs3=[[Ionikos F.C.|Ionikos]]\n|managerclubs4=[[PAOK F.C.|PAOK]]\n|managerclubs5=[[AEK Athens F.C.|AEK Athens]]\n|managerclubs6=[[Ionikos F.C.|Ionikos]]\n|managerclubs7=[[Ukraine national football team|Ukraine]]\n|managerclubs8=[[FC Moscow|Moscow]]\n|managerclubs9=[[Ukraine national football team|Ukraine]]\n|managerclubs10=[[FC Dynamo Kyiv|Dynamo Kyiv]]\n}}\n\n'''Oleg Vladimirovich Blokhin''', or '''Oleh Volodymyrovych Blokhin''' ({{lang-uk|\u041e\u043b\u0435\u0301\u0433 \u0412\u043e\u043b\u043e\u0434\u0438\u0301\u043c\u0438\u0440\u043e\u0432\u0438\u0447 \u0411\u043b\u043e\u0445\u0456\u0301\u043d}}, {{lang-rus|\u041e\u043b\u0435\u0301\u0433 \u0412\u043b\u0430\u0434\u0438\u0301\u043c\u0438\u0440\u043e\u0432\u0438\u0447 \u0411\u043b\u043e\u0445\u0438\u0301\u043d}}; born 5 November 1952) is a former [[Ukraine|Ukrainian]] football player and manager. Blokhin was formerly a standout [[Striker (association football)|striker]] for [[Dynamo Kyiv]] and the [[Soviet Union national football team|Soviet Union]].\n\nHe holds the all-time top goalscorer record for both Dynamo Kyiv (266 goals) and the Soviet Union national team (42 goals), as well as being the overall top goalscorer in the history of the [[Soviet Top League]] (211 goals). He is also the only player to have been [[Cap (sport)|capped]] over [[List of footballers with 100 or more caps|100 times]] for the Soviet Union and holds Dynamo's appearance record with 582 appearances during his 18-year spell at the club. With Dynamo, Blokhin won eight [[List of Soviet and Russian football champions|Soviet league titles]], five [[Soviet Cup|national cups]] and two [[European Cup Winners' Cup]]s. He also competed for the Soviet Union at the [[Football at the 1972 Summer Olympics|1972]] and [[Football at the 1976 Summer Olympics|1976]] [[Football at the Summer Olympics|Olympic Games]] and [[1982 FIFA World Cup|1982]] and [[1986 FIFA World Cup|1986]] [[FIFA World Cup]]s. During his playing career he won the [[Soviet Footballer of the Year]] award three times and the [[Ukrainian Footballer of the Year]] award nine times (both records). In 1975, he was named European Footballer of the Year, winning the [[Ballon d'Or]], becoming the second Soviet and the first Ukrainian player to achieve such a feat.\n\nAs a coach, he has had two spells in charge of the [[Ukraine national football team|Ukrainian national team]], managing the team at the [[2006 FIFA World Cup]] and [[UEFA Euro 2012]].\n\nIn 2011, Blokhin, together with [[Igor Belanov]] and [[Vitaliy Starukhin]] were named as \"the legends of Ukrainian football\" at the Victory of Football awards.<ref>http://www.bulvar.com.ua/arch/2011/51/4ef313ba6efb7/</ref>\n\n== Career ==\nBlokhin was born in [[Kiev]], the capital of the [[Ukrainian SSR]], in 1952 to a [[Russians|Russian]] father from [[Moscow]] and [[Ukraine|Ukrainian]] mother.<ref name=\"terrikon\">[http://www.terrikon.dn.ua/posts/7212 \u041e\u043b\u0435\u0433 \u0411\u043b\u043e\u0445\u0438\u043d: \u00ab\u041c\u043e\u0441\u043a\u0432\u0430\u00bb \u0434\u043e\u043b\u0436\u043d\u0430 \u0431\u044b\u0442\u044c \u0432 \u0442\u0440\u043e\u0439\u043a\u0435 \u043f\u0440\u0438\u0437\u0451\u0440\u043e\u0432]//www.terrikon.dn.ua</ref>\n\n=== Playing ===\nBlokhin was one of the greatest forwards in the world throughout the 1970s, hitting the target regularly through a period of great success at his hometown club [[Dynamo Kyiv]] and becoming the greatest goalscorer in the history of the Soviet League, which was one of Europe's strongest. Normally a forward or winger, Blokhin was most renowned for possessing exceptional pace.\n\nBlokhin played during most of his career for [[FC Dynamo Kyiv|Dynamo Kyiv]], becoming the [[Soviet Union|USSR]] national championship's all-time leader and goalscorer with 211 goals, as well as making more appearances than any other player with 432 appearances. He won the championship 8 times. He led Dynamo to the [[UEFA Cup Winners' Cup]] in 1975 and 1986, scoring a goal in each final. Blokhin is also the USSR national football team's most [[cap (sport)|capped]] player with 112 caps, as well as their all-time leading goalscorer with 42 goals; he played in the [[1982 FIFA World Cup|1982]] and [[1986 FIFA World Cup|1986]] [[FIFA World Cup]]s where he scored 1 goal in each. He was one of the first Soviet players to play abroad, signing for [[Austria]]'s [[Vorw\u00e4rts Steyr]] in 1988, he also played in [[Cyprus]] with [[Aris Limassol|Aris]].\n\nIn 1979 Blokhin played a couple of games for the [[Ukraine national football team|Ukraine]] at the Spartakiad of the Peoples of the USSR.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20150319200631/http://football.lg.ua/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=6685:1979spartakiadanarodovsssrros&catid=212:sovietua79&Itemid=775 Football at the 1979 Spartakiad of the Peoples of USSR]</ref>\n\n=== Coaching ===\nAfter retiring as a player, Blokhin coached Greek clubs [[Olympiacos F.C.|Olympiacos]] (Under him they won the [[Greek Cup]] and the [[Greek Super Cup]] in 1992), [[PAOK F.C.|PAOK]], [[AEK Athens F.C.|AEK Athens]], and [[Ionikos F.C.|Ionikos]].\n\nHe began serving as the head coach of the [[Ukraine national football team|Ukrainian national team]] in September 2003. Under his leadership, Ukraine [[2006 FIFA World Cup qualification (UEFA)|qualified]] for a major tournament for the first time as an independent nation, reaching the [[2006 FIFA World Cup]] in [[Germany]]. Ukraine reached the quarter-finals of the tournament, losing to eventual champions [[Italy national football team|Italy]]. Following the side's failure to reach [[UEFA Euro 2008]], Blokhin stepped down as coach on 6 December 2007.<ref>[http://uk.reuters.com/article/worldFootballNews/idUKL0689781720071206 Soccer-Blokhin quits as Ukraine coach] by Mikhail Volobuyev, Gennady Fyodorov and Ken Ferris,  [[Reuters]], 6 December 2007</ref>\n\nOn 14 December 2007, he was named head coach of [[FC Moscow]].<ref>[http://soccernet.espn.go.com/news/story?id=490600&cc=5739 FK Moscow hire former Ukraine manager Blokhin] ESPNsoccernet 14 December 2007</ref> The club finished 9th (from 16) and after the season ended Blokhin was fired from the club.<ref>[http://www.sports.ru/football/6293328.html \u0411\u043b\u043e\u0445\u0438\u043d \u043e\u0441\u0432\u043e\u0431\u043e\u0436\u0434\u0435\u043d \u043e\u0442 \u043e\u0431\u044f\u0437\u0430\u043d\u043d\u043e\u0441\u0442\u0435\u0439 \u0433\u043b\u0430\u0432\u043d\u043e\u0433\u043e \u0442\u0440\u0435\u043d\u0435\u0440\u0430 \u00ab\u041c\u043e\u0441\u043a\u0432\u044b\u00bb]. Sports.ru. 26 November 2008. Retrieved 2 January 2011.</ref> At the end of the season, Blokhin announced that if he knew how things would go in FC Moscow, he would have never signed there. This was because the club released many important players without Blokhin's permission yet still had many high expectations.<ref>[http://www.sports.ru/football/6206389.html \u041e\u043b\u0435\u0433 \u0411\u043b\u043e\u0445\u0438\u043d: \u00ab\u0415\u0441\u043b\u0438 \u0431\u044b \u0437\u043d\u0430\u043b, \u043a\u0430\u043a \u0431\u0443\u0434\u0443\u0442 \u0434\u0435\u043b\u0430\u0442\u044c\u0441\u044f \u0434\u0435\u043b\u0430 \u0432 \u043a\u043e\u043c\u0430\u043d\u0434\u0435, \u0442\u043e \u0432\u0435\u0441\u043d\u043e\u0439 \u0431\u044b \u043d\u0435 \u043f\u0440\u0438\u0448\u0435\u043b \u0432 \u00ab\u041c\u043e\u0441\u043a\u0432\u0443\u00bb]. Sports.ru. 16 November 2008. Retrieved 2 January 2011.</ref> Others said that the reason Blokhin failed in FC Moscow was that he and the press didn't have a friendly relationship, and because of that the press was constantly attacking Blokhin and that damaged his status among the players.<ref>[http://www.sports.ru/football/6358902.html \u0413\u0435\u043d\u043d\u0430\u0434\u0438\u0439 \u041b\u0438\u0442\u043e\u0432\u0447\u0435\u043d\u043a\u043e: \u00ab\u0413\u043e\u0432\u043e\u0440\u0438\u043b \u0411\u043b\u043e\u0445\u0438\u043d\u0443, \u0447\u0442\u043e \u0435\u0433\u043e \u0431\u0443\u0434\u0443\u0442 \u0442\u0440\u0430\u0432\u0438\u0442\u044c\u00bb]. Sports.ru. 4 December 2008. Retrieved 2 January 2011.</ref>\n\nOn 21 April 2011 Blokhin was again appointed head coach of the Ukrainian national team.<ref>[http://www.skysports.com/story/0,19528,19692_6888233,00.html Ukraine appoint Blokhin], [[Sky Sports]] (21 April 2011)</ref><ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20110426133526/http://football.uk.reuters.com/leagues/european/news/2011/04/21/LDE73K1AD.php Oleg Blokhin appointed Ukraine coach], [[Reuters]] (21 April 2011)</ref> He led the team in [[UEFA Euro 2012]] on home soil, beating [[Sweden national football team|Sweden]] but exiting at the [[UEFA Euro 2012 Group D|group stage]] after defeats to [[France national football team|France]] and [[England national football team|England]].\n\nOn 25 September 2012, [[Dynamo Kyiv]] signed Blokhin to lead the club for the next four years.<ref name=BBBIU17414/> His final matches in charge of Ukraine were [[2014 FIFA World Cup qualification (UEFA)|World Cup qualifiers]] against [[Moldova national football team|Moldova]] and [[Montenegro national football team|Montenegro]] in October 2012.<ref name=BtillOCNToU>[http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/2012/soccer/09/25/dynamo-kiev-oleh-blokhin.ap/index.html Dynamo Kyiv signs Blokhin as coach for 4 years], [[Sports Illustrated]] (25 September 2012)</ref> Blokhin was dismissed as Dynamo's manager by the club's President [[Ihor Surkis]] on 17 April 2014 because of the \"unsatisfactory results of the team\".<ref name=BBBIU17414>[http://en.interfax.com.ua/news/sport/201114.html Dynamo president sacks Blokhin for poor performance], [[Interfax-Ukraine]] (17 April 2014)</ref> The day before, in a press conference after Dynamo had lost a match against [[Shakhtar Donetsk]], Blokhin had already stated that he had decided to resign.<ref name=BBBIU17414/> Under his leadership Dynamo never qualified (a rare occasion for the club) for the [[UEFA Champions League]] and performed poorly in the [[UEFA Europa League]].<ref name=BBBIU17414/> In his first year his team finished third in the [[Ukrainian Premier League]] and in his second year (when he was fired) Dynamo was seven points behind Ukrainian Premier League leaders [[FC Dnipro Dnipropetrovsk|Dnipro Dnipropetrovsk]] and [[Shakhtar Donetsk]].<ref name=BBBIU17414/>\n\n==Career statistics==\n\n===Club===\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n|-\n!rowspan=\"2\" width=\"100\"|Club\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Season\n!colspan=\"2\"|League\n!colspan=\"2\"|Cup\n!colspan=\"2\"|Europe\n!colspan=\"2\"|Super Cup\n!colspan=\"2\"|Total\n|-\n!width=\"40\"|Apps\n!width=\"40\"|Goals\n!width=\"40\"|Apps\n!width=\"40\"|Goals\n!width=\"40\"|Apps\n!width=\"40\"|Goals\n!width=\"40\"|Apps\n!width=\"40\"|Goals\n!width=\"40\"|Apps\n!width=\"40\"|Goals\n|-\n|rowspan=\"20\"|'''[[FC Dynamo Kyiv|Dynamo Kyiv]]'''\n|[[Soviet Top League 1969|1969]]\n|1||0||-||-||-||-||-||-||1||0\n|-\n|[[Soviet Top League 1970|1970]]\n||-||-||1||0||-||-||-||-||1||0\n|-\n|[[Soviet Top League 1971|1971]]\n|1||0||-||-||-||-||-||-||1||0\n|-\n|[[Soviet Top League 1972|1972]]\n|27||14||2||0||6||1||-||-||35||15\n|-\n|[[Soviet Top League 1973|1973]]\n|29||18||8||4||5||1||-||-||42||23\n|-\n|[[Soviet Top League 1974|1974]]\n|29||20||4||3||9||5||-||-||42||28\n|-\n|[[Soviet Top League 1975|1975]]\n|28||18||-||-||8||5||-||-||36||23\n|-\n|[[Soviet Top League 1976|1976]]\n|19||8||1||0||8||2||-||-||28||10\n|-\n|[[Soviet Top League 1977|1977]]\n|29||17||3||2||2||0||1||0||35||19\n|-\n|[[Soviet Top League 1978|1978]]\n|26||13||8||4||4||0||-||-||38||17\n|-\n|[[Soviet Top League 1979|1979]]\n|24||17||6||1||4||1||-||-||34||19\n|-\n|[[Soviet Top League 1980|1980]]\n|33||19||7||3||2||0||-||-||42||22\n|-\n|[[Soviet Top League 1981|1981]]\n|29||19||7||3||6||1||1||0||43||23\n|-\n|[[Soviet Top League 1982|1982]]\n|24||10||3||0||4||0||-||-||31||10\n|-\n|[[Soviet Top League 1983|1983]]\n|31||10||1||0||2||0||-||-||34||10\n|-\n|[[Soviet Top League 1984|1984]]\n|30||10||6||2||-||-||-||-||36||12\n|-\n|[[Soviet Top League 1985|1985]]\n|29||12||2||1||9||5||-||-||40||18\n|-\n|[[