|03/2000\n|align=\"center\"|01/2002\n| x || x || x || x || \n|\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|[[Ukraine national football team|Ukraine]]\n|{{flagicon|Ukraine}}\n|align=\"center\"|01/2003\n|align=\"center\"|12/2007\n{{WDL|46|21|14|11}}\n|Won qual.group [[2006 FIFA World Cup qualification (UEFA)#Group 2|for 2006]], Reached [[2006 FIFA World Cup#Quarter-finals|2006 World Cup quarter-finals]]\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|[[FC Moscow|Moscow]]\n|{{flagicon|Russia}}\n|align=\"center\"|12/2007\n|align=\"center\"|11/2008\n{{WDL|30|9|11|10}}\n|\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|[[Ukraine national football team|Ukraine]]\n|{{flagicon|Ukraine}}\n|align=\"center\"|04/2011\n|align=\"center\"|2012\n{{WDL|12|5|3|4}}\n|Eliminated at group stage of [[Euro 2012]]\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|[[Dynamo Kyiv]]\n|{{flagicon|Ukraine}}\n|align=\"center\"|09/2012\n|align=\"center\"|03/2014\n{{WDL|58|32|10|16}}\n|\n|}\n\n== Politics ==\nIn 1998 Blokhin was elected to [[Verkhovna Rada]] (Ukraine's [[parliament]]) for [[Hromada (political party)|Hromada]].<ref name=DenCommi>[http://www.day.kiev.ua/270204/ Oleh Blokhin: \"I have scored all of my goals\"], [[Den (newspaper)|Den]] (1998)</ref> He joined Hromada while still being a member of the [[Communist Party of Ukraine]].<ref name=DenCommi/> In 2002, Blokhin was elected to Verkhovna Rada for a second term. In October 2002, he joined the [[United Social Democratic Party of Ukraine]].\n\n== Family ==\nBlokhin's father, Vladimir Ivanovich Blokhin, is a native of [[Moscow]], a veteran of the [[World War II]], survivor of the [[Leningrad blockade]], and a former Soviet law enforcement agent. Vladimir Blokhin later worked as a sports functionary for the Soviet Dynamo Society. Blokhin's mother Katerina Zakharivna (''n\u00e9e'' Adamenko) is from a village in the [[Borodyanka Raion]]. She originally worked at a Kyiv sewing factory, but eventually discovered hidden athletic talents and became the Soviet champion in [[track and field]] as well as pentathlon. After retiring from sports, she became a staff member at one of Kyiv's universities.\n\nBlokhin was married to [[Irina Deriugina]], a top coach and former world champion in [[rhythmic gymnastics]], but the couple divorced in the early 1990s. Blokhin and Deriugina have a daughter, singer [[Iryna Blokhina]], who wrote and performed the Euro 2012 anthem.<ref>[http://tabloid.pravda.com.ua/news/4ebd28fd5427b/ \u0414\u043e\u043d\u044c\u043a\u0430 \u0411\u043b\u043e\u0445\u0456\u043d\u0430 \u0437\u0430\u0441\u043f\u0456\u0432\u0430\u0454 \u0433\u0456\u043c\u043d \"\u0404\u0432\u0440\u043e-2012\" (The daughter of Blokhin will sing the Euro 2012 anthem)] with photo. TabloID. 11 November 2011</ref>\n\nBlokhin and his second wife, Angela, have two daughters, Hanna (born 2001) and Katerina (born 2002).<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.sport-express.ru/newspaper/2002-09-27/10_1/ |script-title=ru:\u041e\u043b\u0435\u0433 \u0411\u043b\u043e\u0445\u0438\u043d: \u041c\u0435\u0441\u0442\u043e \u0412 \u0418\u0441\u0442\u043e\u0440\u0438\u0438 |trans-title=Oleg Blokhin: Place in History |work=Sport-Express |author=Yuri Yuris |date= 27 September 2002 |accessdate=25 February 2015 |language=ru}}</ref>\n\n==Honours==\n\n===Club===\n\n;[[FC Dynamo Kyiv|Dynamo Kyiv]]\n*[[Soviet Top League]] (8): [[1971 Soviet Top League|1971]], [[1974 Soviet Top League|1974]], [[1975 Soviet Top League|1975]], [[1977 Soviet Top League|1977]], [[1980 Soviet Top League|1980]], [[1981 Soviet Top League|1981]], [[1985 Soviet Top League|1985]], [[1986 Soviet Top League|1986]]\n*[[Soviet Cup]] (5): 1974, 1978, 1982, 1985, 1987\n*[[USSR Super Cup]]: (3): 1981, 1986, 1987\n*[[UEFA Cup Winners Cup]] (2): [[1975 European Cup Winners' Cup Final|1975]], [[1986 European Cup Winners' Cup Final|1986]]\n*[[UEFA Super Cup]]: [[1975 European Super Cup|1975]]; Runner-up: [[1986 European Super Cup|1986]]\n\n===Individual===\n* [[Unified Sports Classification System of the USSR and Russia|Merited Master of Sports]] (1975)\n* [[Merited Coach of Ukraine]] (2005)\n* [[Ballon d'Or]]: [[1975 Ballon d'Or|1975]]\n* [[International Olympic Committee|IOC]] European Footballer of the Season: 1974\u201375<ref>{{cite web|url=https://footballgreatones.files.wordpress.com/2017/06/ksuf-92.pdf|title=Best European footballers by season|publisher=Ukrainian Football|author1=Volodymyr Banyas|date=25 August 2015|accessdate=2 June 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170823170312/https://footballgreatones.files.wordpress.com/2017/06/ksuf-92.pdf|archive-date=23 August 2017|url-status=dead}} ([[Ukrainian language|ukr.]])</ref>\n* [[Golden Foot]]: 2009, as a [[Golden Foot#Award legends|legend]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.goldenfoot.com/legends.php?l=en|title=Legends|publisher=Golden Foot|accessdate=23 September 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150925120930/http://www.goldenfoot.com/legends.php?l=en|archivedate=25 September 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n* [[Soviet Footballer of the Year]] (3): 1973, 1974, 1975\n* [[Ukrainian Footballer of the Year]] (9): 1972, 1973, 1974, 1975, 1976, 1977, 1978, 1980, 1981\n* [[Soviet Top League]] top scorer (5): 1972, 1973, 1974, 1975, 1977\n* [[Soviet Top League]] All-Time Goals and Appearances Leader\n* [[Soviet Cup]] All-Time Goals\n* [[UEFA Cup Winners' Cup 1985\u201386]] top scorer<ref>[http://www.rsssf.com/ec/ec2tops.html Cup Winners Cup Topscorers]. Rsssf.com (18 December 2003). Retrieved 2 January 2011.</ref>\n* [[European Cup 1986\u201387]] second place on top scorers list.<ref>[http://www.rsssf.com/ec/ec198687det.html#cc European Champions' Cup 1986\u201387 \u2013 Details]. Rsssf.com (17 January 2008). Retrieved 2 January 2011.</ref>\n* [[USSR national football team]] All-Time Goals and Caps Leader\n* Ukraine's [[UEFA Jubilee Awards|Golden Player]] representative<ref>[http://www.uefa.com/uefa/news/Kind=256/newsId=130150.html]  {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20050317084104/http://www.uefa.com/uefa/news/Kind=256/newsId=130150.html |date=17 March 2005 }}</ref